---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why won't you just top up the gas?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Because it is illegal under the Ozone Protection and Synthetic Greenhouse Gas Management Act 1989 to charge refrigerant into a system with a known or suspected leak without first repairing the leak. The Act is administered federally and ARCtick licence-holders are bound by it. Beyond the legality, topping up just funds another release of R32 or R410A into the atmosphere within months, and your power bill keeps climbing because the system is undercharged again. We will not do it — and if anyone offers to, they should not have an ARC licence."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does the two-stage sniffer-and-UV-dye process work?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Stage one is an electronic refrigerant sniffer — a hand-held detector calibrated to R32 or R410A that beeps when it picks up vapour. We sweep every joint, flare and braze on the system slowly. If the leak is large enough, the sniffer finds it within 15 minutes. Stage two, for slow leaks the sniffer cannot isolate, is UV dye: a fluorescent additive charged into the system that bleeds out at the leak site and shows up under a UV torch over the following 24 to 72 hours of run-time. We come back, hit the system with the torch, and the leak point lights up green-yellow."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What does an honest leak-found re-gas quote look like in Cairns?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "It has four line items separated out so you can see what you are paying for. First, the leak-detection callout — usually a fixed fee plus a return visit fee if UV dye is needed. Second, the leak repair, priced by labour hours and parts (a flare re-make is cheaper than a brazed-joint repair on a coil). Third, the evacuation — pulling vacuum on the system to 500 microns and holding for 30 minutes to verify integrity. Fourth, the refrigerant charge by weight in grams, at a transparent per-kilogram rate. Total for a typical slow-leak fix on a Cairns split is between 580 and 950 dollars."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How does Cairns wet-season climate affect leak detection?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Humidity makes the sniffer noisier — water vapour can give false positives on some older detectors. We use heated-diode sniffers calibrated for high-humidity conditions, which are much more reliable in Cairns from December to April. The other wet-season factor is corrosion: salt-aerosol pinholes on the outdoor coil are the most common slow-leak source in Trinity Beach, Yorkeys Knob and along the Esplanade, and they only show up after the coil has been carrying salt for three or four wet seasons. We see two to three of these a week through the peak."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout
  title="Refrigerant leak detection in Cairns — sniffer and UV dye process for tropical aircon"
  description="The two-stage leak-detection process for a Cairns aircon losing gas, why we don't top up and walk away, what the Ozone Act says about refrigerant handling, and what an honest leak-found quote looks like."
  canonical="https://cairnsairconcleaning.com.au/refrigerant-leak-detect-cairns/"
